+## Solution
+
+### Strategic Analysis & Variant Selection
+
+Three archetypes were considered (variant gate decided autonomously per the
+benchmark's non-interactive rule; rationale recorded here):
+
+- **Variant A — Quick fix.** Inline everything: snapshot case in
+  `applyJournalEvents`, a single `compactJournal` in `run-journal.ts`, CLI logic
+  inline in `cli.ts`, auto-trigger inline. Pros: smallest diff. Cons: the
+  "shared by engine and CLI" + "exact protocol" + "refusal rules" requirements
+  push the refusal/lock logic and the summary formatting into the CLI, mixing
+  concerns; harder to test the protocol in isolation. Risk: the engine's own
+  auto-compaction would trip the active-lock refusal (self-refusal). Best for:
+  trivially-scoped changes — which this is NOT.
+- **Variant B — Architecturally-correct (SELECTED).** Layered:
+  (1) `run-journal.ts` owns the *core* crash-safe protocol `compactJournal`
+  (with a test-only fault hook) + the snapshot-seeded suffix-only replay,
+  keeping the single-replayer invariant; (2) `commands.ts` owns the shared
+  *operation* `compactRun` (refusal rules: active lock via `isRunLive`,
+  unreplayable journal, run-not-found) used by the CLI; (3) `cli.ts` is a thin
+  `runs compact` wrapper that only parses args and formats the summary line;
+  (4) the engine reads `eventsSinceSnapshot()` from the writer and calls the
+  core `compactJournal` directly at the `executeLevel` boundary (the engine
+  legitimately holds the lock, so it bypasses the manual active-lock refusal).
+  Pros: each requirement maps to one seam; protocol/refusal/format each unit
+  testable; no self-refusal. Cons: more functions. Best for: a prescriptive
+  multi-surface durability feature — exactly this task.
+- **Variant C — Best long-term.** B plus a pluggable compaction-policy
+  abstraction, multi-version snapshot migration framework, configurable
+  strategies, and an MCP `compact` tool. Pros: future-proof. Cons: over-engineered
+  and partly OUT OF SCOPE (no multi-generation backups, no batch/cross-run,
+  no compression). Discarded.
+
+**Decision: Variant B.** Variant A collapses into B because the task's own
+constraints (single replayer, shared engine+CLI operation, exact protocol,
+two refusal cases, self-compaction by the engine) force the layering; A's
+"inline" shortcut would re-introduce the self-refusal bug and scatter the
+protocol. C violates explicit out-of-scope bounds. Trade-off accepted: a few
+more small functions in exchange for isolated, individually-testable seams and
+zero risk of the engine refusing its own compaction.
+
+### Files to Create / Modify
